article.headline: Liberty send reeling shock to 0-6 start
article.linkText: Liberty remain on a roll with win over Shock
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Crystal Robinson scored 19 points and
reserve Becky Hammon added 17 as the New York Liberty beat the
Detroit Shock 70-63 on Sunday night.

	   Tari Phillips added 15 points for New York (5-2), which has won
five of six since an opening-night loss in Los Angeles, while Kay
Whitmore scored 11.

	   "I think we have some veteran leaders on this team, while
Detroit is still young,'' Robinson said. "We didn't panic -- we
knew that we had a long way to go, but that we'd be fine if we
stepped it up and played hard.''

	   The Shock (0-6) extended their team record for the worst start
to a season.

	   "Obviously, this isn't the start you want,'' Detroit coach Greg
Williams said. "But we know that Charlotte started 1-10 last year
and made it to the championship finals. But it isn't ideal -- not
with our next four on the road. We need a win badly right now.''

	   Rookie Swin Cash led the Shock with 14 points and Deanna Nolan
had 13.

	   Detroit's Wendy Palmer added nine points and a career-high 15
rebounds to become the fifth WNBA player to reach 1,000 career
rebounds, joining Lisa Leslie, Tina Thompson, Vicky Bullet and
Yolanda Griffith.

	   "We've been having trouble rebounding, so I wanted to focus on
that tonight,'' Palmer said. "A thousand rebounds is nice, but
that's something I'll think about after my career. I'm thankful
that I've been able to play in this league for six years, but I've
also been on losing teams for six years.''

	   Detroit led by as many as 14 in the first half, but needed
Nolan's buzzer-beating jumper to take a 33-23 halftime lead. The
Shock outrebounded New York 25-10 in the half, led by Palmer's
nine.

	   Palmer scored the first basket of the second half, but New York
answered with a 24-10 run to take a 47-45 lead with 11:09 to play.

	   "They are playing without a true point guard, so we were able
to press them and get back into the game,'' New York coach Richie
Adubato said. "We gambled with a press and caught them on a night
when they weren't knocking shots down.''

	   New York increased the margin to as many as nine points, holding
Detroit scoreless for nearly five minutes.

	   Five straight points from Cash pulled Detroit within 60-57 with
3:47 to play, but Phillips scored and Astou Ndiaye-Diatta missed
two free throws, allowing New York to put the game away.

	   "They were more aggressive than us in the first half, so we
knew we had to play better in the second,'' Hammon said. "We
caused them some trouble with the zone, and we hit some big shots
in the end.''
